{"type":"message","id":"a0500425","parentId":"00f6ae17","timestamp":"2026-03-13T01:20:26.888Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Okay, let me try to figure out how to handle this cron job for img-gen-1.\n\nFirst, the user sent a cron message: \"CHECK_IMG_QUEUE: Check the image generation queue and process any pending requests. Run: node /data/img-gen/img-claim.js img-gen-1 — if a request is returned (not null), process it following your SOUL.md workflow. Generate the image in Gemini, download it, call img-complete.js when done, then check the queue again for more pending requests.\"\n\nThe current time is Friday, March 13th, 2026 — 9:19 AM (Asia/Kuala_Lumpur). So this is a scheduled task to check the queue.\n\nFrom the SOUL.md file, img-gen-1's workflow is:\n\n1. Claim a request with node /data/img-gen/img-claim.js img-gen-1.\n2. If null, queue is empty, exit.\n3. If request, craft a prompt, generate in Gemini, download image.\n4. Mark complete with img-complete.js.\n\nSo the first step is to run the img-claim.js command. Let me check the tools available. The exec function can run shell commands. So I need to call exec with the command \"node /data/img-gen/img-claim.js img-gen-1\".\n\nIf the command returns a request (not null), then proceed to generate the image. The next step is to get the MultiLogin X profile ID. The SOUL.md mentions using:\n\nnode -e \"const c=JSON.parse(require('fs').readFileSync('/data/img-gen/google-accounts.json','utf8')); console.log(c['img-gen-1'].mlProfileId);\"\n\nBut since this is a cron job, maybe the script handles that part. However, according to the workflow in SOUL.md, Step 2 is to get the profile ID. But perhaps the img-claim.js returns the necessary info, including the profile ID? Wait, the SOUL.md says:\n\n\"2 — Get Your MultiLogin X Profile ID\n```bash\nnode -e \"const c=JSON.parse(require('fs').readFileSync('/data/img-gen/google-accounts.json','utf8')); console.log(c['img-gen-1'].mlProfileId);\"\n```\nUse this as <PROFILE_ID> in all dispatch.js calls.\"\n\nBut in the context of the current task, maybe the request JSON from img-claim.js includes the profile ID? Or does the agent need to fetch it separately? The user's cron message says \"follow your SOUL.md workflow,\" so I should follow each step.\n\nWait, looking back at the SOUL.md workflow:\n\nStep 1: Claim a request.\n\nStep 2: Get your MultiLogin X profile ID.\n\nSo after claiming a request, the agent needs to get the profile ID from the google-accounts.json file.\n\nBut since this is an automated cron job, maybe the profile ID is already known and stored in the script. However, according to the instructions, the agent must get it dynamically each time.\n\nSo the steps are:\n\n1. Run img-claim.js to get the request.\n2. If not null, get the profile ID by reading the json file.\n3. Then proceed to generate the image using Gemini.\n\nBut the user's instruction says \"if a request is returned (not null), process it following your SOUL.md workflow.\" So the next step is to follow the SOUL.md steps.\n\nBut the user is asking for a summary as plain text. So the agent needs to output a summary of what it's doing, and if there's a request, process it.\n\nWait, the task says: \"Return your summary as plain text; it will be delivered automatically.\"\n\nSo the agent should execute the steps and report the result.\n\nFirst, run node /data/img-gen/img-claim.js img-gen-1.\n\nIf the result is null, then the queue is empty, and the summary should be \"Queue empty. Exiting.\"\n\nIf there is a request, then proceed to process it.\n\nBut since this is a cron job, the agent must handle each request in the queue.\n\nSo the agent should:\n\n- Check the queue.\n- If there's a request, process it (generate image, etc.), then check again until queue is empty.\n\nBut the user's task is to do one check and process any pending requests. So the cron job runs once and processes all available requests in the queue.\n\nNow, t